1
00:00:54,250 --> 00:00:56,578
Grand Hotel. Grand Hotel.

2
00:00:57,479 --> 00:00:59,891
The time is 01:35 am.

3
00:01:00,853 --> 00:01:02,564
Yes, this is the night operator.

4
00:01:03,337 --> 00:01:04,695
I'll give you the night clerk.

5
00:01:06,112 --> 00:01:07,413
Hello? Night clerk speaking.

6
00:01:07,806 --> 00:01:08,885
Alright. Yes.

7
00:01:09,657 --> 00:01:11,558
Has Mr Mark Stone arrived?
- Not yet.

8
00:01:11,897 --> 00:01:14,090
Miss Hallie Hobart in?
- She's not in, Mr Thorne.

9
00:01:14,293 --> 00:01:16,981
Did you ring her?
- Yes. But she's not in, Mr Thorne.

10
00:01:17,254 --> 00:01:17,840
Ah.

11
00:01:18,388 --> 00:01:20,147
These salesmen won't
take no for an answer.

12
00:01:20,704 --> 00:01:21,850
I'll give her a buzz.

13
00:01:22,393 --> 00:01:23,838
Room 417, please.

14
00:01:27,145 --> 00:01:30,187
How many times?
Miss Hobart is out. O-U-T.

15
00:01:30,389 --> 00:01:33,031
That's just what I wanted to
know, girlie. How are you all?

16
00:01:33,228 --> 00:01:35,110
Say, you're not allowed in here.
- No?

17
00:01:36,828 --> 00:01:38,874
Well I've never seen your
face but I know your voice.

18
00:01:39,071 --> 00:01:41,302
Charlie Thorne of the
Bellside Harvester Company.

19
00:01:41,665 --> 00:01:44,052
I just blew in tonight.
- Yes, you were here last year.

20
00:01:44,747 --> 00:01:46,452
Sure. Where's Hallie Hobart?

21
00:01:46,947 --> 00:01:49,407
Well, if you don't tell anybody.
She's out on business.

22
00:01:49,796 --> 00:01:51,350
You know Mr Kent Carr, don't you?

23
00:01:51,648 --> 00:01:54,265
Sure. Kent Carr of the
Carr Harvester Company.

24
00:01:54,462 --> 00:01:55,828
What's she doing out with him?

25
00:01:56,197 --> 00:01:58,243
They're out with some customers.
You know, farmers.

26
00:01:59,182 --> 00:02:01,878
Selling machinery.
Hallie is helping me put the deal over.

27
00:02:02,453 --> 00:02:04,725
Hallie makes a lot of money that
way. You know, percentage.

28
00:02:05,348 --> 00:02:08,167
Say, is Mr Mark Stone
one of the rustics?

29
00:02:08,468 --> 00:02:09,855
Who?
- Mark Stone.

30
00:02:10,241 --> 00:02:11,000
No.

31
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:14,555
She still works in the barber shop?
- Yes, she's still manicuring.

32
00:02:15,055 --> 00:02:16,276
Trimming them good, eh?

33
00:02:16,473 --> 00:02:18,466
She must have a lot of
money in the old sock now.

34
00:02:18,881 --> 00:02:20,758
Plenty. She's a smart girl.

35
00:02:22,272 --> 00:02:22,944
Hello?

36
00:02:23,725 --> 00:02:24,511
She's out.

37
00:02:25,527 --> 00:02:27,414
That's young McConnell again.
He's drunk.

38
00:02:27,811 --> 00:02:30,660
He's waiting for Hallie too.
- McConnell the packer's son?

39
00:02:31,073 --> 00:02:34,103
He wanted to marry her, didn't he?
- Sure, and he still does.

40
00:02:34,574 --> 00:02:36,743
He's got plenty of Jack.
- That he has.

41
00:02:37,247 --> 00:02:40,044
You know, last year when Hallie
was away on her vacation.

42
00:02:40,521 --> 00:02:44,011
He had her room all fixed
up by an interior decorator.

43
00:02:44,475 --> 00:02:45,774
Have you seen it?
- No.

44
00:02:46,055 --> 00:02:47,871
Does that mean he's
got the run of the place?

45
00:02:48,068 --> 00:02:51,069
No. He doesn't get to
first base with Hallie.

46
00:02:51,724 --> 00:02:53,493
She's smart, Hallie is.
- Right.

47
00:02:56,233 --> 00:02:56,916
Hello?

48
00:02:57,637 --> 00:02:58,366
Alright.

49
00:03:01,324 --> 00:03:03,625
Hello? Ice water in 620.

50
00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:05,370
He's the drunkest thing.

51
00:03:05,731 --> 00:03:08,118
You must get quite an
earful on this board, baby.

52
00:03:08,373 --> 00:03:09,703
Plenty. I could write a book.

53
00:03:09,972 --> 00:03:11,788
Would you like to leave
a message for Hallie?

54
00:03:11,985 --> 00:03:15,127
No, I'll hang around. I've got to
see her. I want to talk business.

55
00:03:15,717 --> 00:03:17,854
Why don't you wait up in her room: 417?

56
00:03:18,272 --> 00:03:21,095
I'll have Mike let you in.
You can give him a quarter.

57
00:03:21,292 --> 00:03:23,565
You know, young McConnell is
waiting down there in the lobby.

58
00:03:23,762 --> 00:03:25,206
That's a great idea.

59
00:03:25,471 --> 00:03:27,189
You have what's called a brain, baby.

60
00:03:27,573 --> 00:03:28,444
Grand Hotel.

61
00:03:28,745 --> 00:03:31,133
I said you've got what
they call a brain.

62
00:03:31,497 --> 00:03:33,528
Grand Hotel.
- Well, let it go.

63
00:03:36,321 --> 00:03:37,709
Mike. On the phone.

64
00:03:38,547 --> 00:03:39,848
Have you a reservation, sir?

65
00:03:40,112 --> 00:03:41,306
Yes, the name is Stone.

66
00:03:42,011 --> 00:03:44,028
Yes. There's a reservation
here for a Mr Mark Stone.

67
00:03:45,239 --> 00:03:47,084
I'm David. That's my brother.
He's not coming.

68
00:03:48,582 --> 00:03:50,698
David Stone. 418.
- Yes, sir.

69
00:03:51,655 --> 00:03:52,584
Right this way.

70
00:03:52,876 --> 00:03:54,206
Goodnight, sir.
- Goodnight.

71
00:03:55,014 --> 00:03:56,978
Gee, I wish had half that
young fellow's money.

72
00:03:57,391 --> 00:03:59,843
He might like to have half of
anybody's money. Who is he?

73
00:04:00,258 --> 00:04:02,645
The son of Ezra Stone, the richest
wheat farmer in the state.

74
00:04:02,942 --> 00:04:04,587
Looks as if he hadn't change for a dime.

75
00:04:04,882 --> 00:04:06,286
Just good old farm stock.

76
00:04:11,251 --> 00:04:13,017
Hallie Hobart in yet? Give her a buzz.

77
00:04:13,214 --> 00:04:14,995
I told you, Mr McConnell. She's not in.

78
00:04:15,192 --> 00:04:17,657
Give her another buzz anyhow.
I had a date with her. Go on.

79
00:04:17,905 --> 00:04:19,974
Hey. Why not run along home, buddy.

80
00:04:20,501 --> 00:04:21,595
The lady isn't in.

81
00:04:22,183 --> 00:04:23,398
You know what time it is?

82
00:04:23,947 --> 00:04:24,933
A quarter to two.

83
00:04:26,237 --> 00:04:27,344
Who wants to know?

84
00:04:27,624 --> 00:04:29,727
I'm the house officer and
you're making too much noise.

85
00:04:29,950 --> 00:04:31,857
I did, eh? I don't like detectives.

86
00:04:32,193 --> 00:04:33,294
They're a snoopy lot.

87
00:04:33,491 --> 00:04:36,295
Now look here young fellow. We don't
want any trouble here. Go on, get out.

88
00:04:37,517 --> 00:04:39,100
It's terrible. I'm going to bed.

89
00:04:39,429 --> 00:04:41,303
Leave them to me.
I'll get rid of them alright.

90
00:04:42,408 --> 00:04:43,971
Just .. just a minute.

91
00:04:44,191 --> 00:04:46,923
You must say goodnight to the lady now
because we're going home to go to bed.

92
00:04:47,572 --> 00:04:48,721
Goodnight, Mr Olsen.

93
00:04:48,918 --> 00:04:51,171
Say goodnight to the lady.
We're going home to go to bed.

94
00:04:51,368 --> 00:04:53,721
Goodnight, Mr France. We had
a perfectly charming time.

95
00:04:54,072 --> 00:04:55,365
I thoroughly enjoyed it.

96
00:04:56,479 --> 00:04:59,197
I kiss your hand, madame.

97
00:05:02,716 --> 00:05:04,143
Let me help you up.

98
00:05:11,219 --> 00:05:13,372
Everything is fine.
Now, I'll see you in the morning.

99
00:05:15,094 --> 00:05:16,287
Don't forget.
- Yes.

100
00:05:17,724 --> 00:05:19,752
Mike .. get him out of here.

101
00:05:22,225 --> 00:05:24,356
I've got a date with you, Hallie.
- Yes, I know. I know.

102
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:27,006
What's the idea?

103
00:05:28,347 --> 00:05:29,648
I've got a date with Hallie.

104
00:05:30,821 --> 00:05:31,480
Who?

105
00:05:31,677 --> 00:05:33,965
Charlie Thorne of the Bellside
Harvester Company.

106
00:05:34,162 --> 00:05:35,635
Yes, I know Charlie Thorne, but ..

107
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:37,605
He said it was Business.

108
00:05:37,802 --> 00:05:39,346
Business? At this hour of the night?

109
00:05:39,665 --> 00:05:41,312
It was alright to let him in, wasn't it?

110
00:05:41,509 --> 00:05:44,228
No, Mike. You know better than to
let a man in my room at this hour.

111
00:05:44,811 --> 00:05:46,429
Miss Hallie. I'm sorry.

112
00:05:46,940 --> 00:05:49,746
Sure, I wouldn't do anything wrong.
- You wouldn't, would you.

113
00:05:50,191 --> 00:05:51,193
Stupid Irishman.

114
00:05:51,418 --> 00:05:53,594
Ah bless your little heart.

115
00:05:54,195 --> 00:05:56,079
Stupid man.

116
00:05:58,711 --> 00:06:00,517
Hello Charlie.
- Hello.

117
00:06:01,801 --> 00:06:03,205
How are you, little fellah?

118
00:06:03,843 --> 00:06:05,774
Say, how did you get in here?
You've got a nerve.

119
00:06:06,014 --> 00:06:07,993
I busted in to talk business to you.

120
00:06:08,234 --> 00:06:09,267
Business? Oh, no.

121
00:06:09,555 --> 00:06:12,061
I'm through with business for today.
I was in the shop at nine.

122
00:06:15,428 --> 00:06:16,983
This will only take you a minute.

123
00:06:17,339 --> 00:06:18,940
No, Charlie. Save it for the morning.

124
00:06:19,295 --> 00:06:20,782
Run along, there's a dear.

125
00:06:21,621 --> 00:06:23,960
Alright, we'll let it go. Goodnight.

126
00:06:26,149 --> 00:06:28,759
Johnny, I didn't mean to be
rude but I'm all worn out.

127
00:06:30,285 --> 00:06:31,301
Now wait a minute.

128
00:06:31,498 --> 00:06:33,121
You're not doing me any favor, baby.

129
00:06:33,458 --> 00:06:36,403
I just wanted to let you in
on a little quick, sure dough.

130
00:06:37,180 --> 00:06:38,338
Some quick, sure dough?

131
00:06:38,994 --> 00:06:40,336
Listen, you old crosspatch.

132
00:06:41,492 --> 00:06:42,647
I'm all in, you see.

133
00:06:43,154 --> 00:06:45,266
Tomorrow I have to get
up bright and early.

134
00:06:45,755 --> 00:06:47,594
But .. suppose you tell me all about it.

135
00:06:48,016 --> 00:06:49,803
And I'll go in there
and get comfortable.

136
00:06:50,925 --> 00:06:52,046
Comfortable?
- Yes.

137
00:06:52,554 --> 00:06:55,370
Comfortable? I haven't
been comfortable in a week.

138
00:06:57,150 --> 00:06:58,600
You got a drink for me?

139
00:06:59,002 --> 00:07:00,515
Me? No, I never drink the stuff.

140
00:07:00,847 --> 00:07:02,625
I hate it.
- It's a great pity.

141
00:07:03,114 --> 00:07:04,607
I'll try to struggle along.

142
00:07:06,115 --> 00:07:07,188
What's on your mind?

143
00:07:07,930 --> 00:07:09,811
You've heard of Ezra Stone, haven't you?

144
00:07:10,028 --> 00:07:10,957
Yes. Who is he?

145
00:07:11,299 --> 00:07:13,115
He's the biggest wheat
farmer in the country.

146
00:07:13,312 --> 00:07:17,200
His son Mark Stone is due here and I'm
going to sell him some machinery.

147
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:18,852
What do you want me to do?

148
00:07:19,721 --> 00:07:21,242
This fellow Mark Stone.

149
00:07:22,300 --> 00:07:24,640
Comes from a strait-laced family, see.

150
00:07:25,624 --> 00:07:28,017
Narrow-minded, you know.
- Yeah, I know.

151
00:07:28,876 --> 00:07:31,709
They've got so much money,
the banks won't take it.

152
00:07:31,968 --> 00:07:33,355
They have to pay storage on it.

153
00:07:33,552 --> 00:07:34,880
Good to hear it.

154
00:07:35,077 --> 00:07:37,338
He's a tough trader, Hallie.
And I thought ..

155
00:07:37,549 --> 00:07:38,650
I'm way ahead of you.

156
00:07:38,847 --> 00:07:41,052
You want me to take him to
a party and loosen him up.

157
00:07:41,249 --> 00:07:42,493
And help you get the deal.

158
00:07:42,899 --> 00:07:45,055
Am I right, professor?
- You're a mind reader.

159
00:07:45,615 --> 00:07:48,858
You know, when those
bozos fall, they fall hard.

160
00:07:49,771 --> 00:07:51,491
And you're the baby ..

161
00:07:52,223 --> 00:07:53,717
That can make them stumble.

162
00:07:54,606 --> 00:07:56,527
And when Mr Stone is stumbled ..

163
00:07:57,074 --> 00:07:59,117
How much in it for the
little girl who trips him?

164
00:07:59,549 --> 00:08:00,800
I'll give you one percent.

165
00:08:01,746 --> 00:08:04,216
Nothing doing. I can get two
percent from Kent Carr.

166
00:08:04,779 --> 00:08:06,143
Oh, Kent Carr.

167
00:08:07,050 --> 00:08:08,327
Yes. Kent Carr.

168
00:08:09,068 --> 00:08:10,369
He's out after the same guy.

169
00:08:11,191 --> 00:08:12,044
Well, snap.

170
00:08:12,772 --> 00:08:14,385
And you were too tired?

171
00:08:14,639 --> 00:08:16,484
I'm never too tired for
a bit of big business.

172
00:08:18,472 --> 00:08:21,956
I'll give you three percent but not a
word to Kent Carr or anybody else.

173
00:08:22,153 --> 00:08:23,025
Okay with me.

174
00:08:23,346 --> 00:08:25,572
I don't like Kent Carr
anyway. He's too fresh.

175
00:08:26,144 --> 00:08:28,189
You keep the boys in
their places, don't you.

176
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:29,916
Yes, it's the only way.

177
00:08:30,751 --> 00:08:32,882
A man will give you more if
you don't give him anything.

178
00:08:33,330 --> 00:08:34,833
Not even a little promise?

179
00:08:35,675 --> 00:08:36,816
Now, Charlie.

180
00:08:39,496 --> 00:08:41,095
When does your Mr Stone roll in?

181
00:08:41,437 --> 00:08:43,077
Tonight, or tomorrow morning.

182
00:08:43,671 --> 00:08:44,970
It's a big order, Hallie.

183
00:08:45,312 --> 00:08:47,185
Well .. I could do with the money.

184
00:08:48,162 --> 00:08:49,704
I'm saving every cent now.

185
00:08:50,130 --> 00:08:51,630
What are you saving up for?

186
00:08:51,944 --> 00:08:53,274
To get out of this burgh.

187
00:08:53,608 --> 00:08:55,452
Charlie, I've got my
life all planned out.

188
00:08:56,161 --> 00:08:57,248
I'm off to Paris.

189
00:08:57,629 --> 00:08:58,697
Yeah?
- Uhuh.

190
00:08:59,093 --> 00:09:00,229
Why to Paris?

191
00:09:01,201 --> 00:09:02,888
I'm going to make something of myself.

192
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:04,667
I'm going to be someone.

193
00:09:04,994 --> 00:09:07,937
You've got enough saved up
now to take a trip to Paris.

194
00:09:08,623 --> 00:09:10,133
But it isn't just a trip I want.

195
00:09:10,498 --> 00:09:11,571
I'm going for keeps.

196
00:09:11,768 --> 00:09:13,670
Charlie, I take French
lessons twice a week.

197
00:09:14,242 --> 00:09:16,390
And Charlie .. look .. come here.

198
00:09:20,376 --> 00:09:21,105
Clothes.

199
00:09:21,795 --> 00:09:22,953
Aren't they marvelous?

200
00:09:23,778 --> 00:09:24,491
Paris.

201
00:09:27,663 --> 00:09:28,679
What's the matter?

202
00:09:28,876 --> 00:09:30,957
Where did you get the wardrobe?

203
00:09:31,678 --> 00:09:32,834
What do you mean?

204
00:09:33,545 --> 00:09:34,565
Commissions.

205
00:09:34,960 --> 00:09:37,406
And I've got an interest in Madam
Bernstein's shop downstairs.

206
00:09:37,969 --> 00:09:39,927
I believe you, Hallie.
- You should.

207
00:09:43,632 --> 00:09:46,424
You think you're smart, don't you?
- Of course I'm smart.

208
00:09:46,883 --> 00:09:49,418
Someday, you'll meet some
nice kid and fall in love.

209
00:09:49,773 --> 00:09:51,759
<i>Then</i> we'll see how smart you are.

210
00:09:51,956 --> 00:09:53,774
Me and love? Bunk. Never.

211
00:09:54,202 --> 00:09:57,251
It sneaks up on you, this love business.
- Not on this baby it won't.

212
00:09:58,136 --> 00:10:00,246
I know too much about men. I hate them.

213
00:10:00,857 --> 00:10:02,518
Someday you'll marry one and then ..

214
00:10:02,821 --> 00:10:03,941
Me? No, sir.

215
00:10:04,390 --> 00:10:06,869
The only interest I have
in your fair sex is ..

216
00:10:07,199 --> 00:10:08,994
The old bankroll.
- Check.

217
00:10:10,417 --> 00:10:12,005
And then for Paris. France.

218
00:10:13,484 --> 00:10:16,121
Little fellah, you'll get
anything you go after.

219
00:10:16,875 --> 00:10:17,874
You bet I will.

220
00:10:18,467 --> 00:10:20,828
Don't forget mister Mark Stone.

221
00:10:21,091 --> 00:10:22,902
Alright, partner. Mister Mark Stone.

222
00:10:24,033 --> 00:10:24,819
Goodnight.

223
00:10:25,178 --> 00:10:25,964
Goodnight.

224
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:28,701
Pleasant dreams.
- Thanks, Charlie.

225
00:11:02,998 --> 00:11:03,670
Hello?

226
00:11:04,362 --> 00:11:05,406
Hello. Hello, dear.

227
00:11:06,613 --> 00:11:08,291
You did? That's too bad.

228
00:11:08,811 --> 00:11:09,769
What time is it?

229
00:11:10,442 --> 00:11:11,118
Oh.

230
00:11:12,924 --> 00:11:15,091
Well call me about .. eight, will you.

231
00:11:15,631 --> 00:11:16,638
Yes, I know it.

232
00:11:17,111 --> 00:11:18,384
I'll catch you up sometime.

233
00:11:19,251 --> 00:11:19,894
Sure.

234
00:11:20,603 --> 00:11:22,225
For a long time, yes.

235
00:11:22,773 --> 00:11:23,559
Goodnight.

236
00:12:23,009 --> 00:12:24,605
Hello Charlie, when did you get in?

237
00:12:24,804 --> 00:12:26,347
Look, look. The farmer's friend.

238
00:12:26,544 --> 00:12:27,680
And how.
- Kent Carr.

239
00:12:27,877 --> 00:12:29,207
How are you?
- Alright, boy.

240
00:12:29,514 --> 00:12:32,346
Monk, Seen Hallie this morning?
- Not seen her. We're not speaking.

241
00:12:33,552 --> 00:12:36,417
If you mean Hallie Hobart, she's down
at Madam Bernstein's dress shop.

242
00:12:36,809 --> 00:12:39,208
Much obliged. Start me on
the second car-load, baby.

243
00:12:42,007 --> 00:12:43,066
Home James.

244
00:12:43,472 --> 00:12:44,745
And don't spare the horses.

245
00:12:47,704 --> 00:12:48,943
What are you laughing at?

246
00:12:49,140 --> 00:12:51,643
When I get to Paris I'll have one
of these every night of the week.

247
00:12:51,842 --> 00:12:53,593
Take me with you.
- You, in Paris?

248
00:12:54,084 --> 00:12:57,062
Come on. Make it snappy, will you Queen.
He's in the barber shop now.

249
00:12:57,940 --> 00:12:58,637
Who?

250
00:12:58,834 --> 00:13:00,737
Young David Stone.
This is the kid brother.

251
00:13:00,962 --> 00:13:02,738
He's come out to buy
